liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: That was a question put to Philip Lowe by committee member Allegra Spender, who asked if there was an interest rate the RBA could lift to so inflation returned to that 2-3% band by 2024. Mr Lowe said there was no magic number that could guarantee that being achieved by that deadline. "It's not an extra 25 basis points to get back by 2024," he said. "It's maybe a full percentage point, I'd say, at least. "[I] tend to think roughly that 100 basis points give you a quarter point a bit more or less. [It] depends a little bit on the environment and we can see that where other countries, other economies, their interest rates are actually significantly higher."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: What would it take to get inflation back to target by 2024?

children.content: That was a question put to Philip Lowe by committee member Allegra Spender, who asked if there was an interest rate the RBA could lift to so inflation returned to that 2-3% band by 2024.
Mr Lowe said there was no magic number that could guarantee that being achieved by that deadline.
"It's not an extra 25 basis points to get back by 2024," he said.
"It's maybe a full percentage point, I'd say, at least.

"[I] tend to think roughly that 100 basis points give you a quarter point a bit more or less. [It] depends a little bit on the environment and we can see that where other countries, other economies, their interest rates are actually significantly higher."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Just circling back to another interesting point we hear a lot from the RBA about unemployment. Philip Lowe was asked about whether an increase in the unemployment rate was still likely, given inflation was coming down now and the RBA is so focused on preserving the gains in the labour market. Incoming RBA governor Michele Bullock has been criticised for saying unemployment could hit 4.5% earlier this year. Philip Lowe said even though the unemployment rate was holding steady at 3.5%, it was still the central bank's view that unemployment would have to tick up slightly. "We're now moving into the next phase of getting inflation down [and] it will involve slower growth in unit labour costs," he said. "Mean unit labour costs at the moment are increasing very rapidly. That's the difference between nominal wage growth and productivity. "Our sense is that for inflation to come back to 2 to 3%, then we're going to have to see some moderation in growth in unit labour costs, and that's why the pick-up in productivity is so important, and we're also expecting after wage growth picks up a bit more then there'll be some moderation in growth in wages. "We're hoping that the rise in unemployment will be modest but to get services price inflation back to a more sustainable rate. "Our judgment is that that's likely to be accompanied with some modest rise in unemployment."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Rising unemployment rate remains likely as inflation moderates

Incoming RBA governor Michele Bullock has been criticised for saying unemployment could hit 4.5% earlier this year.
Philip Lowe said even though the unemployment rate was holding steady at 3.5%, it was still the central bank's view that unemployment would have to tick up slightly.
"We're now moving into the next phase of getting inflation down [and] it will involve slower growth in unit labour costs," he said.
"Mean unit labour costs at the moment are increasing very rapidly. That's the difference between nominal wage growth and productivity.

"Our sense is that for inflation to come back to 2 to 3%, then we're going to have to see some moderation in growth in unit labour costs, and that's why the pick-up in productivity is so important, and we're also expecting after wage growth picks up a bit more then there'll be some moderation in growth in wages.
"We're hoping that the rise in unemployment will be modest but to get services price inflation back to a more sustainable rate.
"Our judgment is that that's likely to be accompanied with some modest rise in unemployment."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The Australian share market is following Wall Street's fairly lacklustre close, with the major indices opening almost totally flat. The benchmark ASX 200 was down just 1 point to 7,356 points at 10:24am AEST. The broader All Ordinaries was up 2 points to 7,571. The main drag was energy, which gave up some of yesterday's huge gains with a 1 per cent decline early on. Mining stocks were also in the red, with BHP down 0.5%, while Rio Tinto and Fortescue were both off a tad over 1%. The banking sector was generally lifting the market, with Westpac's 0.5% rise the best of the big four, and only NAB flat to slightly lower. AMP was backing up yesterday's strong gains with another 3.7% rise to $1.1925, after a well-received result released yesterday. Consumer cyclicals were up, with embattled casino operator Star surging nearly 19% to $1.1575.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: ASX follows flat finish on Wall Street with subdued start

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Russia has launched its first Moon-landing spacecraft in 47 years, in a bid to be the first power to make a soft landing on the lunar south pole, a region believed to hold coveted pockets of water ice. A Soyuz 2.1v rocket carrying the Luna-25 craft blasted off from the Vostochny cosmodrome, 5,550km east of Moscow, at 2:11am Moscow time. Here's the moment of the launch: The lander is due to touch down on the Moon on August 23, Russia's space agency says. The Russian lunar mission, the first since 1976, is racing against India, which sent up its Chandrayaan-3 lunar lander last month, and more broadly with the United States and China.
